he South African Defence Force (SADF); archival material, including military intelligence surveillance of the ECC; ECC campaigning material, press reports and other pro-state propaganda. The analysis is informed by perspectives in sociology, international relations, history and from work on contemporary militarised societies such as those in Israel and Turkey. This book also explores the interconnections between militarisation, sexuality, race, homophobia and political authoritarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAnti-apartheid movementszSouth AfricaxHistory. 0aDraft resisterszSouth Africa. 0aMasculinityzSouth Africa. 0aSociology, MilitaryzSouth Africa. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  a1984 Citizenship Act.  aEnd Conscription Campaign.  aSouth Africa's militarisation.  aanti-apartheid activism.  aapartheid-era.  acompulsory military service.  afeminist activism.  ahomophobia.  apeace movement.  apolitical authoritarianism.  apre-1994 South African society.  aprogressive militarisation.  aradical political subjectivities.  atransformative political act.  atransgressive sub-cultural space.  awar making.  awhite femininity.  awhite masculinity.1 aConway, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129598423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129598/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013